{"id":"1001.3084","submitter":"Luis Mendo","authors":"Luis Mendo","title":"Asymptotically optimum estimation of a probability in inverse binomial\n  sampling under general loss functions","comments":"Journal of Statistical Planning and Inference. Published online 2012","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1016/j.jspi.2012.03.026","report-no":null,"categories":"math.ST stat.TH","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The optimum quality that can be asymptotically achieved in the estimation of\na probability p using inverse binomial sampling is addressed. A general\ndefinition of quality is used in terms of the risk associated with a loss\nfunction that satisfies certain assumptions. It is shown that the limit\nsuperior of the risk for p asymptotically small has a minimum over all\n(possibly randomized) estimators. This minimum is achieved by certain\nnon-randomized estimators. The model includes commonly used quality criteria as\nparticular cases. Applications to the non-asymptotic regime are discussed\nconsidering specific loss functions, for which minimax estimators are derived.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 18 Jan 2010 15:11:59 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 10 Jan 2012 19:53:45 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Mon, 30 Apr 2012 12:08:59 GMT"}],"update_date":"2012-05-01"}
